# 3D Web Effects Without Three.js

Look at this portfolio. The cards tilt, the portrait follows your cursor, the stars drift — all without a single WebGL context.

## The Core Trick: `transform-style: preserve-3d`

```css
body { perspective: 1400px; }

.card {
  transform-style: preserve-3d;
  transition: transform 0.4s cubic-bezier(.22,1,.36,1);
}
```

That's it. Now every child with `translateZ()` lives in 3D space.

## Mouse Tilt in 20 Lines

```js
card.addEventListener('mousemove', e => {
  const r = card.getBoundingClientRect();
  const x = (e.clientX - r.left) / r.width;
  const y = (e.clientY - r.top) / r.height;
  const rx = (y - 0.5) * -10;
  const ry = (x - 0.5) *  10;
  card.style.transform = 
    `perspective(1000px) rotateX(${rx}deg) rotateY(${ry}deg)`;
});

card.addEventListener('mouseleave', () => {
  card.style.transform = '';
});
```

Done. Fluid, 60fps, zero dependencies.

## Keep It Honest

- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`
- Disable on touch devices (no hover)
- Keep rotations under ±10° — more feels cheap

## When You DO Need Three.js

Actual 3D geometry, shaders, particle physics, scene graphs. Not tilt. Not parallax. Not glow.

Simple = better.
